<br>
and none of them are precise.<br>
<br>
The nominal yield of a nuclear device is an approxiamate measure.  The only way to fully know the true yield of the device is to detonate it or one exactly like it (same warhead/bomb class).  Nuclear testing isn't too big nowadays...the majority of current warheads are untested, have only had theoretical computations of their yield done.  A variance of a few kilotons is kinda important in anything other than a destructive setting. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/16/02 4:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=72>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Orion is plagued with bogeymen...</span><hr size=1> While I am a HUGE advocate of nuclear power, I frankly don't &quot;get&quot; everyones apparent fascination with the concept of the Orion.  <br>
<br>
Pusher plate design is a very tough problem to solve, and while I suspect the issue of uniformity and repeatability of the &quot;thrust units&quot; is a solvable one, where are you going to get the chance to proof your concepts?  I suppose enough computer power would let you model accurately, but it seems a scary prospect to test on your actual spacecraft, if you see what I mean.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
No, I think an NTR powered heavy lift booster with a 1000 ton payload capacity combined with a nuclear salt water powered orbital &quot;tug&quot; is the way to go.<br>
<br>
The booster has isp of 3000 or so and is &quot;clean&quot;, the tug has Isp of 6000 or so and is &quot;dirty&quot;.  The tug has a fuel mass fraction of about 80 percent and weighs 1000 tons, and can be carried to orbit in a single launch of the booster.  The tug is used to carry a 200 ton expedition module to wherever you want to go.  The tug with its craft attached has a total delta V of 72 km/sec, which is plenty to get to mars and back in a jiffy quick fashion.  <br>
<br>
When the tug gets back, the booster has lugged up another 800 tons of nuclear saltwater fuel.  To do it all again.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Given this sort of system, which is VERY doable with todays tech, why the obsession with Orions?  <br>
<br>
Me not get it.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :x --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/sick.gif ALT=":x"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
However, if you want to see a fancier and sleeker descendant of the Orion concept, kindly check <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://ffden-2.phys.uaf.edu/213.web.stuff/Scott%20Kircher/fissionfusion.html"> this page. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
The ICAN-II design masses about 710 tons, so could handily serve as the &quot;tug&quot; in the scheme I have outlined above.  The NTR powered booster could pop one of these into orbit effortlessly.<br>
<br>
ALL of this is technology which is not blue-sky science fiction stuff, nor does it require atomic bombs, just the much more benign sounding &quot;fuel pellets.&quot;  <br>
<br>
We have made and run gas core NTR's before.  We have extensive experience with inertially confined fusion pellets.  We have extensive experience with antimatter particle beams.  At this point in time, it is simply a matter of putting all of the pieces together, folks.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
